         <title>Notes</title>
         <ref id="ref1">
            <label>1.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Sylvie Bérard notes that this universe is also invoked in several other of Vonarburg's works, including those found in the<italic>Contes de Tyranaël</italic>(“Fictional Arborescence” 35). It should also be noted that the B<sc>ridge</sc>C<sc>ycle</sc>is historically rooted in the 1970s and 1980s, comprising the earlier stage of Vonarburg's career, though a significant volume of the stories appeared in the following decades. From the 1990s to the first decade of the twenty-first century, Vonarburg's life and work were dedicated in large part to the T<sc>yranaël</sc>(<year>1996–1997</year>) and R<sc>eine de</sc>M<sc>émoire</sc>(Queen of Memory,<year>2005–2007</year>) pentalogies.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">The “novum” is a techo-scientific innovation or a socio-cultural configuration which distinguishes the fictional world from the empirical world (Suvin 4).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref3">
            <label>3.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">For an engaging analysis of the representation of myth and science in Vonarburg's B<sc>ridge</sc>C<sc>ycle</sc>, see Gillian Benson's study.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref4">
            <label>4.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">On entropy and teleology, see Karen Hellekson (especially 249–50) and Hayden White. See also Henriet (58–61) on the “evenemential” and the “providential.”</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref5">
            <label>5.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">On diegetic encyclopedias, see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Umberto Eco</string-name>
               </person-group>. On<italic>xénoencyclopedias</italic>, see Richard Saint-Gelais (especially 138–41 and 206–12).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref6">
            <label>6.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">This conceptualization of the Voyage and, by extension, of life evokes Blaise Pascal's seventeenth-century wager, according to which the rational being would be more advantageously rewarded through a belief in God, should the possibility prove true, than disadvantaged by the potential error of this judgment. In other words, the benefits of belief outweigh the risks. See especially note 233 (65–69).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref7">
            <label>7.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Resolution in a story that appears entropic is subject both to choices (of an individual or a network of individuals) and to chance and coincidences of a metaphysical or cosmogonical nature. The control that one can exert over history is thus always partial. A story characterized by the teleological tendency is inescapably ruled by the immanent idea of an unavoidable destiny. Any attempt to escape that destiny in order to forestall the predetermined ending can only fail, since compensatory elements intervene to ensure that all comes to pass according to the logic of a pre-established linearity from the beginning to the end (Serruys, 67).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref8">
            <label>8.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">These poles—escape and subversion—are also found in the thought of Paul Ricoeur on the utopian impulse (see Serruys, 82).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
